==Personal life==
[[File:Kristaps Porzingis in 2017 summer.png|thumb|175px|Kristaps Porziņģis in 2017, when he was in Latvia]]
Porziņģis was born to parents who had experience playing the game of [[basketball]]. Tālis, his father, competed semi-professionally before becoming a [[bus driver]]. His mother, Ingrīda, was previously on [[Latvia women's national basketball team|Latvia women's youth national basketball team]].<ref name=aol /> Kristaps's older brother, [[Jānis Porziņģis|Jānis]], also played professionally,<ref name=eurocup /> while Mārtiņš, who is approximately fifteen years older than his youngest sibling, was also an avid player.<ref name=aol>{{cite web|last1=Weitzman|first1=Yaron|title=NBA Draft Watch: The Kristaps Porzingis Experience|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2015/06/22/nba-draft-watch-the-kristaps-porzingis-experience/21199493/|website=[[AOL]]|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> In a 2017 ''[[E:60]]'' documentary on Porziņģis' life, his parents revealed that they had another son, Toms, who was born four years before Kristaps and died at 14 months. Through an interpreter, Ingrīda said about Toms' death, "It felt like a bulldozer had run over my life. We had two other children who we had to care for. We had to live on. After Kristaps was born, it was like he had to live for two lives."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2017/06/25/the-quiet-porzingis-family-tragedy/ |title=‘Had to live for two lives’: The tragedy that shaped Kristaps Porzingis |first=Marc |last=Berman |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |date=25 June 2017 |accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref>

Jānis Porziņģis competed at the [[European professional club basketball system|European 2nd tier]] [[EuroCup Basketball|EuroCup]] level, the same level in Europe that Kristaps later played at, in one game,<ref>[http://www.eurocupbasketball.com/eurocup/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=JTZ&seasoncode=U2004 PORZINGIS, JANIS SUPERFUND KAPFENBERG BORN: 13 JULY, 1982 NATIONALITY: LATVIA.]</ref> and played European professional club basketball in various national leagues, including the [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]],<ref>[http://web.legabasket.it/player/?id=POR-JAN-82 Janis Porzingis|#10 Naz. di Nascita: LAT Naz. Sportiva: LAT Città di Nascita: Liepaja Altezza: 201 cm Data di Nascita: 13/07/1982 Peso: 102 kg] {{it icon}}</ref> for more than 10 years. He is known to mentor his younger brother on and off the court and often called him after playing games for Cajasol Sevilla in Spain. Kristaps talked about the relationship in an interview, "We'd break down the details. We watched the film together. He's always pushing me to work hard. We just spend a lot of time together and we just talk about basketball all the time..."<ref name=interview>{{cite web|last1=Robbins|first1=Josh|title=A Q-and-A with NBA Draft prospect Kristaps Porzingis|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/orlando-magic/os-kristaps-porzingis-interview-20150622-story.html#page=1|website=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> The elder Porziņģis helped him train in the summer and work out in the gym in preparation for international competition in 2012.<ref name=eurocup />

Following two seasons in Spain and almost two years living in Seville, Porziņģis was able to speak Spanish far more fluently. Porziņģis is thus fluent in three different languages, including English.<ref name=eurocup /> An NBA executive said, "He speaks great English and I don't see it being that difficult of a transition off the court."<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotto: Kristaps Porzingis Transcends the European Stereotype|url=http://www.sheridanhoops.com/2015/06/19/scotto-kristaps-porzingis-transcends-the-european-stereotype/|website=SheridanHoops.com|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> In October 2016, Porziņģis signed a shoe deal with [[Adidas]], the most lucrative deal for a European player. He made the switch to Adidas after partnering with [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] for his rookie season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ingrassia|first=Nunzio|url=https://nypost.com/2016/10/06/kristaps-porzingis-reportedly-signs-huge-shoe-deal-and-not-with-nike/|title=Kristaps Porzingis signs huge sneaker deal with Adidas|work=NYPost.com|date=6 October 2016|accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rooney|first=Kyle|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kristaps-porzingis-officially-signs-with-adidas-after-nike-fails-to-match-offer-news.24978.html|title=Kristaps Porzingis Officially Signs With Adidas After Nike Fails To Match Offer|work=hotnewhiphop.com|date=25 October 2016|accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref>

Porziņģis is a [[association football|football]] fan and supports his hometown team [[FK Liepāja]], as well as [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and former club [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]].<ref name=Twitter>{{cite web|last1=Porziņģis|first1=Kristaps|title=Twitter account|url=https://twitter.com/kporzee/status/612093491703906309|website=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> He is also an avid fan of ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]'', which he plays regularly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/kristaps-porzingis-journey-skinny-sleepy-kid-latvian-hero/story?id=40234604|title=Kristaps Porzingis' journey from skinny, sleepy kid to Latvian hero|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=29 June 2016|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=8 August 2018}}</ref>

===Rape allegation===
In March 2019, it was publicly revealed that a woman accused Porziņģis of raping her at the [[Sky (skyscraper)|Sky]] building in February 2018, hours after he tore his ACL. The woman reportedly told police she waited more than a year to come forward because she had discussed getting a $68,000 payout from Porziņģis to keep quiet. Porziņģis' attorney, Roland G. Riopelle, publicly denied the claim, and said he had previously referred the case to federal authorities due to the "accuser's extortionate demands".<ref>{{cite web|last=Begley|first=Ian|last2=MacMahon|first2=Tim|last3=Young|first3=Royce|title=Report: Porzingis accused of rape in New York|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26401287/report-porzingis-accused-rape-new-york|website=[[ESPN]]|date=30 March 2019|accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>

